  <div class="markdown-body f5 mb-2">
    <p>Python is a dynamically typed programming language designed by Guido van Rossum. Much like the programming language Ruby, Python was designed to be easily read by programmers. Because of its large following and many libraries, Python can be implemented and used to do anything from webpages to scientific research.</p>
  </div>

                  <p>A description is incomplete. It should mention:</p>

<p>"There are two main patterns to support high availability: fail-over and replication. "</p>

                <div class="Box-body comment-body markdown-body position-relative overflow-hidden pt-3" style="max-height:200px">
                  <p>I redirected a friend to this page because I was 100% sure that it must have good Python tutorials, because the pages of other Awesome lists have it.</p>
<p>But sadly, this has not. I would really be happy to see some good tutorials for each group (Complete Beginner, Programmers who want to learn a new language, and so on).</p>
<p>I know few, but here would be the perfect place to collect the best as a gr</p>

                <div class="Box-body comment-body markdown-body position-relative overflow-hidden pt-3" style="max-height:200px">
                  <p>There are some interesting algorithms in simulation from Physics, Chemistry, and Engineering especially regarding Monte Carlo simulation: Heat Bath algorithm, Metro-Police algorithm, Markov Chain Monte Carlo, etc.</p>

                  <div
                    class="position-absolute right-0 left-0 bottom-0 text-center"

                <relative-time datetime="2020-04-14T17:55:33Z" class="no-wrap">Apr 14, 2020</relative-time>

                <div class="Box-body comment-body markdown-body position-relative overflow-hidden pt-3" style="max-height:200px">
                  <p>There are many pages in the docs that have different overlapping information about error handlers:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/1.1.x/errorhandling/#error-handlers" rel="nofollow">https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/1.1.x/errorhandling/#error-handlers</a></li>
<li><a href="https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/1.1.x/blueprints/#error-handlers" rel="nofollow">https://flask.palletsprojects.com/en/1.1.x/blueprints/#error-handlers</a></li>

</ul>

        </ul>
      </div>
  </div>

              <div class="Box-header f6 text-gray">
                <strong class="text-gray-dark text-bold">
                  saeedalahmari3
                </strong>

                  commented

                <relative-time datetime="2020-04-23T14:04:58Z" class="no-wrap">Apr 23, 2020</relative-time>
              </div>

                <div class="Box-body comment-body markdown-body position-relative overflow-hidden pt-3" style="max-height:200px">
                  <p>In Keras documentation, glorot_uniform says that the initializer is using Glorot Uniform from <a href="http://proceedings.mlr.press/v9/glorot10a/glorot10a.pdf" rel="nofollow">this paper</a>. However, the Keras implementation is totally different from the equation on the paper. Also, there are some arguments such as mode ='fan_avg' is the default. It should be same as the referenced paper. 'fan_sum'. Golort uniform is shown</p>

                  <div
                    class="position-absolute right-0 left-0 bottom-0 text-center"

                <relative-time datetime="2020-03-06T17:27:15Z" class="no-wrap">Mar 6, 2020</relative-time>

                <div class="Box-body comment-body markdown-body position-relative overflow-hidden pt-3" style="max-height:200px">
                  <p>It's not clear from the website's documentation, or the <code>--help</code> output, how to do the following equivalent curl task:</p>
<p><strong>Post a raw JSON query to ElasticSearch:</strong></p>
<pre><code>curl \
    --header "Content-Type: application/json" \
    --request POST \
    --data '{ "_source": [ "restricted_countries.*" ], "query": { "match_all": {} }, "size": 1000 }' \
    'http://localhost:9200/_search'
</code></pre>
<p>T</p>

                <div class="Box-body comment-body markdown-body position-relative overflow-hidden pt-3" style="max-height:200px">
                  <h5>SUMMARY</h5>
<p>apt_repository throws exception "TypeError: instancemethod expected at least 2 arguments, got 0"<br>
This is the same issue than #57195 which has been closed, but still persist.</p>
<p>Please note that I'm fully aware that python 2.6 is old, and debian6 is very old.<br>
However the documentation says that python2.6 is supported for managed nodes (and not for management Host), so this mo</p>

            <h1 class="d-inline flex-auto f3 text-normal lh-condensed">
              <a class="text-gray-dark" href="https://github.com/psf/requests/issues/5371" data-hydro-click="{&quot;event_type&quot;:&quot;explore.click&quot;,&quot;payload&quot;:{&quot;click_context&quot;:&quot;REPOSITORY_CARD&quot;,&quot;click_target&quot;:&quot;ISSUE&quot;,&quot;click_visual_representation&quot;:&quot;BIG_GOOD_FIRST_ISSUE&quot;,&quot;actor_id&quot;:60628828,&quot;record_id&quot;:572641263,&quot;originating_url&quot;:&quot;https://github.com/topics/python&quot;,&quot;user_id&quot;:60628828}}" data-hydro-click-hmac="8c053f8508701793bd68de253ce7b64ce90d3d9a2c83876c098523b606e8ae74" data-ga-click="Explore, go to issue, location:good first issues;size:large;">

            <div class="Box Box--condensed position-relative timeline-comment--caret">
              <div class="Box-header f6 text-gray">
                <strong class="text-gray-dark text-bold">
                  psiyan

                  commented

                <relative-time datetime="2020-02-28T09:46:04Z" class="no-wrap">Feb 28, 2020</relative-time>
              </div>

                <div class="Box-body comment-body markdown-body position-relative overflow-hidden pt-3" style="max-height:200px">
                  <p>When using the url <code>http://docs.python-requests.org/en/latest/</code>, it redirects to <code>https://2.python-requests.org//en/latest/</code> (notice the extra / before <code>en</code>). This causes a HTTP 404.</p>
<h2>Expected Result</h2>
<p>The redirect should be to <code>https://2.python-requests.org/en/latest/</code></p>
<h2>Actual Result</h2>
<p>HTTP 404</p>
<h2>Reproduction Steps</h2>
<p>Try to visit the latest en documentation for requests using the</p>

                  <div
                    class="position-absolute right-0 left-0 bottom-0 text-center"
                    style="background: linear-gradient(to top, rgba(255,255,255,1), rgba(255,255,255,0));"
                  >
                    <a class="btn btn-outline btn-sm mx-auto my-3" data-hydro-click="{&quot;event_type&quot;:&quot;explore.click&quot;,&quot;payload&quot;:{&quot;click_context&quot;:&quot;REPOSITORY_CARD&quot;,&quot;click_target&quot;:&quot;ISSUE&quot;,&quot;click_visual_representation&quot;:&quot;READ_MORE&quot;,&quot;actor_id&quot;:60628828,&quot;record_id&quot;:572641263,&quot;originating_url&quot;:&quot;https://github.com/topics/python&quot;,&quot;user_id&quot;:60628828}}" data-hydro-click-hmac="e908ced1c68ac0404d1cd5c6cd980a1af077f557c8d5ecbf5cee0474d65bb1b7" data-ga-click="Explore, go to issue, location:good first issues;text:read more;size:large;" href="https://github.com/psf/requests/issues/5371">
                      Read more
</a>                  </div>
                </div>
            </div>

                <div class="Box-body comment-body markdown-body position-relative overflow-hidden pt-3" style="max-height:200px">
                  <p>Not sure when this happened but i love the new left-hand side navigation <a href="https://scikit-learn.org/dev/user_guide.html" rel="nofollow">https://scikit-learn.org/dev/user_guide.html</a></p>
<p>(<a class="user-mention" data-hovercard-type="user" data-hovercard-url="/users/adrinjalali/hovercard" data-octo-click="hovercard-link-click" data-octo-dimensions="link_type:self" href="https://github.com/adrinjalali">@adrinjalali</a> did this maybe?)<br>
<a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/449558/79594368-e3a10e00-80aa-11ea-8007-c5628ea84ac9.png"><img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/449558/79594368-e3a10e00-80aa-11ea-8007-c5628ea84ac9.png" alt="image" style="max-width:100%;"></a></p>
<p>However, when clicking the different entries, the result is inconsistent. For some, it shows a TOC that expands the existing toc with m</p>

                    class="position-absolute right-0 left-0 bottom-0 text-center"
                    style="background: linear-gradient(to top, rgba(255,255,255,1), rgba(255,255,255,0));"

                <div class="Box-body comment-body markdown-body position-relative overflow-hidden pt-3" style="max-height:200px">
                  <h3>Description</h3>
<p>When I scrape without proxy, both https and http urls work.<br>
Using proxy through https works just fine. My problem is when I try http urls.<br>
In that moment I get the <code>twisted.web.error.SchemeNotSupported: Unsupported scheme: b''</code> error</p>
<p>As I see, most of the people have this issue the other way around.</p>
<h3>Steps to Reproduce</h3>
<ol>
<li>Scrape a http link with proxy</li>
</ol>
<p>**Expected</p>

<h3>Description</h3>
<p>the docs say that default value for 'model' is "large". in <a href="https://face-recognition.readthedocs.io/en/latest/_modules/face_recognition/api.html#face_encodings" rel="nofollow">fact</a>, it is "small", which makes a different. please correct the docs</p>

                  <h2>The problem</h2>
<p>I copied the arduino integration into <code>custom_components</code>:</p>
<div class="highlight highlight-source-shell"><pre>cp -R /srv/homeassistant/lib/python3.7/site-packages/homeassistant/components/arduino/ /home/homeassistant/.homeassistant/custom_components/</pre></div>
<p>and made homeassistant the owner:</p>
<div class="highlight highlight-source-shell"><pre>sudo chown -R homeassistant:homeassistant arduino/</pre></div>
<h2>Environment</h2>
<p>Latest hass, latest raspbian on Pi 4.</p>
<ul>
<li>Home A</li>
</ul>

                <div class="Box-body comment-body markdown-body position-relative overflow-hidden pt-3" style="max-height:200px">
                  <p>The chat tutorial listed for elixir is outdated. It uses a old version of phoenix and could be confusing to new users who would be learning  a oudated set of syntax, application structure, commands i.e. <code>mix phoenix.create</code> vs. <code>mix phx.create</code>.</p>
<p>Also it's missing some steps. For one this they never do <code>mix ecto.create</code> without which the postgres database is not initialized so the app doesn't wo</p>

            <h1 class="d-inline flex-auto f3 text-normal lh-condensed">
              <a class="text-gray-dark" href="https://github.com/certbot/certbot/issues/7973" data-hydro-click="{&quot;event_type&quot;:&quot;explore.click&quot;,&quot;payload&quot;:{&quot;click_context&quot;:&quot;REPOSITORY_CARD&quot;,&quot;click_target&quot;:&quot;ISSUE&quot;,&quot;click_visual_representation&quot;:&quot;BIG_GOOD_FIRST_ISSUE&quot;,&quot;actor_id&quot;:60628828,&quot;record_id&quot;:612738216,&quot;originating_url&quot;:&quot;https://github.com/topics/python&quot;,&quot;user_id&quot;:60628828}}" data-hydro-click-hmac="7fd302d0983aeb49bb341503cc4596a77e7d94760d653817e3eaaba3798ee49f" data-ga-click="Explore, go to issue, location:good first issues;size:large;">
                Test coverage on macOS
</a>

            </h1>
          </div>

        </div>

        <div class="d-flex">
          <div class="mr-3">
            <img
              class="avatar avatar-user avatar-small"
              alt="bmw"
              src="https://avatars0.githubusercontent.com/u/6504915?v=4"
              width="32"
              height="32"
            >
          </div>
          <div class="flex-auto" style="width: 80%;">
            <div class="Box Box--condensed position-relative timeline-comment--caret">
              <div class="Box-header f6 text-gray">
                <strong class="text-gray-dark text-bold">
                  bmw
                </strong>

                  commented

                <relative-time datetime="2020-05-05T16:35:24Z" class="no-wrap">May 5, 2020</relative-time>
              </div>

                <div class="Box-body comment-body markdown-body position-relative overflow-hidden pt-3" style="max-height:200px">
                  <p>When working on other things, I found that our coverage tests were failing on <code>master</code> on macOS. I quickly fixed this in <a class="issue-link js-issue-link" data-error-text="Failed to load title" data-id="612238133" data-permission-text="Title is private" data-url="https://github.com/certbot/certbot/issues/7972" data-hovercard-type="pull_request" data-hovercard-url="/certbot/certbot/pull/7972/hovercard" href="https://github.com/certbot/certbot/pull/7972">certbot/certbot#7972</a>, but there's nothing stopping us from hitting this problem again in the future. I think we should avoid this because it can be a confusing/frustrating experience, especially for new Certbot developers, to investigate test failures on</p>

                  <div
                    class="position-absolute right-0 left-0 bottom-0 text-center"
                    style="background: linear-gradient(to top, rgba(255,255,255,1), rgba(255,255,255,0));"
                  >
                    <a class="btn btn-outline btn-sm mx-auto my-3" data-hydro-click="{&quot;event_type&quot;:&quot;explore.click&quot;,&quot;payload&quot;:{&quot;click_context&quot;:&quot;REPOSITORY_CARD&quot;,&quot;click_target&quot;:&quot;ISSUE&quot;,&quot;click_visual_representation&quot;:&quot;READ_MORE&quot;,&quot;actor_id&quot;:60628828,&quot;record_id&quot;:612738216,&quot;originating_url&quot;:&quot;https://github.com/topics/python&quot;,&quot;user_id&quot;:60628828}}" data-hydro-click-hmac="9b5ebe42de8bbfab1cdc7e55b52afc92113e4c279fcdce0087df16514cf60655" data-ga-click="Explore, go to issue, location:good first issues;text:read more;size:large;" href="https://github.com/certbot/certbot/issues/7973">
                      Read more
</a>                  </div>
                </div>
            </div>

              <span class="discussion-item-icon border-white-fade-15 ml-0 mr-2">

                <div class="Box-body comment-body markdown-body position-relative overflow-hidden pt-3" style="max-height:200px">
                  <h4>Location of the documentation</h4>
<p><a href="https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/development/code_style.html" rel="nofollow">https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/development/code_style.html</a><br>
<a href="https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/development/contributing.html#code-standards" rel="nofollow">https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/development/contributing.html#code-standards</a></p>
<h4>Documentation problem</h4>
<p>Most of the documentation for the coding style guidelines is limited and in multiple locations. Much of the coding style is in a script.</p>
<h4>Suggested fix for documentation</h4>

                  <div
                    class="position-absolute right-0 left-0 bottom-0 text-center"
                    style="background: linear-gradient(to top, rgba(255,255,255,1), rgba(255,255,255,0));"

                <div class="Box-body comment-body markdown-body position-relative overflow-hidden pt-3" style="max-height:200px">
                  <p>I think listing anti-patterns with some basic reasoning about "why not" is a good idea.</p>
<p>Example - singleton. Although #256 has "won't fix" label</p>
<ul>
<li>it is in PRs section, and people (if searching history at all) are searching issues first.</li>
<li>it was misspelled, Singelton instead of Singleton, therefore impossible to find</li>
</ul>
<p>Listing most popular anti-patterns (without actual implementation) shou</p>

                  <p>In the <a href="https://github.com/jakevdp/PythonDataScienceHandbook/blob/master/notebooks/05.09-Principal-Component-Analysis.ipynb">PCA section</a> there is the following quote:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/47821203/53817403-442fc300-3f5d-11e9-9478-059f7b9afc53.png"><img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/47821203/53817403-442fc300-3f5d-11e9-9478-059f7b9afc53.png" alt="image" style="max-width:100%;"></a><br>
We see that these 150 components account for just over 90% of the variance.</p>
</blockquote>
